            <sic>ṇetrapava</sic>
            <corr>kṣetra-pada</corr>
          </choice><!-- 
L3. M: harija, W: hārila; J: hari(datta). Harīṣa is quite certain and was probably intended for harīśa. 
--><!-- 
L3. M: rānetaka; J: ranetakā; W: rāṭenaka. Again, kāṇanaka is certain from the photo. Some strokes (such as the arms of k) were not filled in with chalk or whatever the white substance is, and are thus not visible in the rubbings the others used. 
--><!-- 
L3. M: (grāmottara)sīmāyāṁ; J. grāmādadhīsīmāyāṁ; W: grāme darau(ka)samayā. Mirashi's reading has merits as a likely emendation. 
--><!-- 
L3. M: (bha)ṭṭi ... metat kṣetrapa(da); J. nāṭyātaṭataṭe ne(kṣe)trapada; W: naddī-taṭa-taṭe tnetrāpava (sic). My reading is quite secure; I assume naṭṭa-taṭa to be a toponym and the second taṭa as a common noun. Mirashi and Jain are probably correct that the unintelligible ṇetrapava was meant for kṣetrapada. 
--><!-- 
L3-4. The phrasing here resembles IN00523, Rudradāsa year 70 and IN00529 Bhuluṇḍa 57. 
--><lb n="4"/>m brāhmadeya<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> ś<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice><unclear>ś</unclear>vatam a-bhāgam a-bhaṭa-prā<unclear>v</unclear>e<unclear>ś</unclear>yam āca<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>drārk<surplus>t</surplus>a-graha-na<choice>
            <sic>nda</sic>
            <corr>kṣa</corr>
          </choice>tra-<choice>
            <sic>sa</sic>
            <corr>tāra</corr>
          </choice><!-- 
L4. M: grahana(kṣe)tra ta. J: grahāvanyamratā(ra). W. graha-ṇanda-tāra. The ligature definitely looks like nda (or nva); probably an engraver's mistake for a clumsily pre-drawn kṣa. At the end, sa is clear in the photo; I assume it is again a carver's mistake for a pre-drawn tāra. 
--><lb n="5"/>kā-kāl<unclear>ī</unclear>na<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> putra-p<choice>
            <sic>o</sic>
            <corr>au</corr>
          </choice>trān<choice>
