              <unclear>e</unclear>
            </sic>
            <corr>ai</corr>
          </choice><unclear cert="low">va</unclear> <unclear>brā</unclear><!-- 
L5. W. bhāgadeyaṁ for bhogāyaivaṁ 
--><!-- 
L5. W. asya sarvva (and bra in the next line, which is wrong); M. asyeda brā, em. asyaidaṁ brā. 
--><lb n="6"/>hmaṇasyo<choice>
            <sic>c</sic>
            <corr>c</corr>
          </choice>itena brahmadeya-krame<unclear>ṇait</unclear>at-kṣetra-padam bhuñjataḫ kr̥ṣata<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><!-- 
L6. M: hmaṇasyocitena brahmadeva kr̥tmatvotkṣetraṁ padambhu(jji)taṁ kr̥ṣata(ḥ), em. brahmadeyaṁ; tatkṣetraṁ. J: hmaṇasyocitena brahmadeya-krame(rṇa) tat kṣetrapadambhuṁjata(śco)pabho. W. brahmaṇasvai vitane brahmadeya kratmatvota pakṣatraṁ padambhūjitamkr̥ṣata. brahmadeva is probably a typo since ya is clear in his rubbing. My reading is quite secure. ṇai in krameṇaitat actually looks like a v with two vowel marks at the top and one on the left of the body; it may have been corrected from va to ṇe/ṇai or vice versa. 
--><!-- 
L6. The ñja in bhuñjataf looks like jā, but there is a very similar one that must also be meant for ñja in l5 of the NM charter of Svāmidāsa, year 65. 
--><lb n="7"/>vapataś ca sarvvair e<unclear>v</unclear>āsmat-pak<unclear>ṣ</unclear>a-ta<unclear>t</unclear>-kul<choice>
            <sic>i</sic>
            <corr>ī</corr>
          </choice>nārakṣik<choice>
            <sic>e</sic>
            <corr>ai</corr>
          </choice><supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> preṣa<unclear>ṇa</unclear>ka-bhaṭa<!-- 
L7. M reads karṣayataśca, emending to karṣayatayaśca (sic!). vapataśca, as read by W, is clear in M's own rubbing. 
--><!-- 
L7. W. āsmat-sakr̥ta-kulīnārakṣake preṣṇika bhaṭa. M reads °ārakṣika (presumably in compound) and presaṇika, emending to ṣa. 
--><lb n="8"/>cchatra-dāṇḍapāśakādibhis <choice>
            <sic>y</sic>
            <corr>s</corr>
          </choice>amanu<choice>
            <sic>janvata</sic>
            <corr>mantavyaṁ</corr>
          </choice>|| baspa bhaṭṭ<unclear>ā</unclear>raka-mah<unclear>ā</unclear>r<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice>j<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice><sic>ṇva</sic><!-- 
L8. J. °bhissamanujanvataḥ| yastu bhaṭṭāraka-mahārājānu W. cchatra candralaṣakādibhisya manujānvataḥ bappa bhaṭṭāraka-mahārājanva. M reads °janvataḥ|| (em. mantavyaṁ), but the two short horizontals are either a visarga or a punctuation mark; latter seems more likely; not both, at any rate. M does not read baspa/bappa. M reads the final nva (which seems clear in his rubbing) as (ṇā)(nu), whatever that may mean. 
--><lb n="9"/>dattaka<sic>pūktāśasaḥ p<unclear>r</unclear>ābheṇabh<unclear cert="low">ū</unclear>luka vijñāya<unclear cert="low">t sa</unclear>bu<unclear cert="low">ha</unclear></sic> va<unclear>r</unclear>ṣe <num value="107"><unclear>
              <g type="numeral">100</g>
            </unclear> 7</num> m<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice><unclear>gha</unclear><!-- 
L9.
M: da(jñā) ta .. .. prā bhā(mā)ṇa(pi) kaloka - (kā dva) vi jñāya saka (kaṁ) (|×) varṣe 107 ma 30. × probably indicates editorial addition.
J: (da)ttaka praṇāśasaḥ pabhavakālika vijñāyasa varṣe 100 7 māgha.
W. dattaka-pratiśasa prabhānakalika vijñāyavarṣa 50 7 māgha.
The above is my reading of the photo. 100 seems more likely to me than 50. 30 cannot be excluded at the end, but since these guys normally use tithis, I don't think it's possible in the context. Hence I prefer gha. There may have been a now obliterated 1 or other simple numeral at the end. No trace of śu or ba.
My best guess at the gibberish is that it was meant for something like this:
yaś ca bhaṭṭāraka-mahārājena dattaka-[/mahārājānudattaka-]bhūbhāgaḥ sa pūrvveṇa bhūmiko vijñeyas sabrahma
but this is still uniterpretable. What is important, however, is that this grant of 107(?) mentions a mahārāja bhaṭṭāraka, of whom we have grants in 102 and 127. And whatever the exact meaning of this is, it seems to speak about land granted earlier by Bhaṭṭāraka. 
--></p>
